the guild.  Even with all the power gaming urges and awesome talent/equipment in KEG, EQ is a very unforgiving game. <br>
<br>
It is fair to say that from the time KEG came to Zeb, we were one of the top two guilds on the server.  But that required a Tremendous amount of time and strain on personal lives to keep proving ourselves day after day.  So what happens next? either EQ consumes the daily life or a break is needed.   Sorry folks, choosing break is much more healthy.  Look around EQ, there are indeed guilds on every server that &quot;own&quot; everything in sight, but even now I would be willing to bet that Sab would call all but 2 or 3 of those guilds sub par.  If there is a guild out there doing something subjectively deemed better than you, all you hear is the negative comparisons from Sab everyday.  No matter if that guild is on another server.  I know this for fact, I have dealt with it first hand.  Hell, just to illustrate my point, I would bet in the two or three weeks KEG has been taking a bit of a siesta, already people are moving us out of the &quot;uber&quot; status.  Do I care? well at first I did, because I do associate a certain amount of pride with accomplishments in game and I would be lieing if I said &quot;being one of the best&quot; didn't give an artificial ego boost....but as I look more deeply into, I really don't.  You can never WIN EQ..no matter what happens, it is an unforgiving game in which you have to prove yourself over and over and over.  Hell, if Fires of Heaven disbanded right now, how long until they faded into the shadows?  Well I can tell you, the first time some new challenge arose that they did not tackle first or second EQ wide, the rumors of them slipping would begin.  At this point in EQ, I am not satisfied enough to stop striving forward, but I am certainly content with the knowledge that if the servers were unplugged tomorrow, I would have been the &quot;best&quot; at some point or another.  If my entire guild goes to AO or Shadowbane or whatever the next biggest thing is, then I will go with them.  Because I can absolutely say beyond the shadow of any doubt....if my guild and friends left this game, there is a good chance I would flounder around for a few days and probably do the cancel as well.  <br>
<br>
Being the best is no fun, if you have no one to share it with.  <br>
<br>
Sorry for the rambling.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/uraene.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Raene</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_redspot.gif BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Battle Druid, Artist</span><br>  Posts: 151<br> <font color=#333333>(6/29/01 12:07:46 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://2amstudios.com/eq/raene/raene01.jpg HEIGHT=183 WIDTH=151></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Sab ponders the state of the game. Poses some questions.</span><hr size=1> It has been said many times by many people that "we all have fun in different ways".  I think Sab (Hi Sab :P) is saying he has fun by beating a game, by being involved with organizations that consistently overcome whatever obstacle Verant sets up as the next pinnacle.  That is as a legitimate reason for playing as any.<br>
<br>
The dillemma occurs when the creators of the game decide that the next pinnacle will require 50+ people cooperating for hours on end repeatedly. It seems that the percentage of "pure gamers" willing to put in hours needed to beat the game (hours that have been described subjectively as monotonous, boring, headbanging-against-the-monitor-frustrating) is in the minority. Is it possible to get 50+ like-minded, dedicated beat-the-game gamers together into one organization? How does one cull the player population in order to get *just* those like-minded gamers?  <br>
<br>
In an online environment where the majority of players have a view of fun that is other than "beat the game", perhaps creating a "pure gamer guild" is the biggest challenge of all.<br>
